properties.areaDesc: Southern Brevard County; Martin; Northern Brevard County; St. Lucie; Indian River; Coastal Volusia
properties.headline: Rip Current Statement issued January 25 at 2:56AM EST until January 25 at 7:00PM EST by NWS Melbourne FL
properties.description:
* WHAT...For the Beach Hazards Statement, rough surf and breaking
waves up to 5 feet. For the High Rip Current Risk, dangerous
rip currents expected.

* WHERE...Coastal Volusia, Brevard, Indian River, St. Lucie, and
Martin counties.

* WHEN...From 7 AM EST this morning through this evening.

* IMPACTS...Rip currents can sweep even the best swimmers away
from shore into deeper water. The rough surf can knock you down
and make you more susceptible to being caught in the seaward
pull of a rip current. Entering the water is strongly
discouraged..
properties.instruction:
Rip currents are powerful channels of water flowing quickly away
from shore, which occur most often at low spots or breaks in the
sandbar and in the vicinity of structures such as jetties and
piers. Heed the advice of lifeguards, beach patrol flags and
signs. Beachgoers are strongly discouraged from entering the surf
today.
